, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Limerick and Cork): variant of   Moore   4.","English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Mory</i>, a pet form of <i>Amauri</i> (see   Amery  ).","English: perhaps also a variant of   Moore   1–3."],"variants":[{"name":"Morrey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Morey  ."]},{"name":"Moore","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>more</i> ‘moor, marsh, fen’ (Old English <i>mōr</i>), hence a topographic name for someone who lived in such a place, or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, as for example Moore in Cheshire or More in Shropshire.","English (of Norman origin): ethnic name from Old French <i>more</i> ‘Moor’, either someone from North Africa or, more often, a nickname for someone thought to resemble a Moor. Compare   Morrell   and   Moreau  .","English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>More</i> (Old French <i>More</i>, <i>Maur</i>, Latin <i>Maurus</i>), originally denoting either ‘Moor’ or someone with a swarthy complexion (compare   Morrell  ,   Morrin  ,   Morris  , and sense 2 above). There was a 6th-century Christian saint of this name."]},{"name":"Moree","meanings":["Altered form of   Morey  .","French (<b>Morée</b>): habitational name from a place so named in Loir-et-Cher."]},{"name":"Morie","meanings":["Altered form of <b>Moree</b>, itself perhaps an altered form of English or French   Morey   (compare 2 below) or of Irish   Morrow  .","English (London): variant of   Morey  . This surname is rare in Britain.","French: unexplained. This surname is rare in France."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Andrew Moray 3rd Lord of Bothwell was born in 1270, in Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Andrew de Moray Justiciar of Scotia, Lord of Petty, was 52 and his mother, de Comyn, was 40. He had at least 1 son. He died after 11 October 1297, in Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1270–after 11 October 1297":"1270–pärast 11. oktoobrit 1297","1240–1332":"1240–1332","1270–1297":"1270–1297","1298–1338":"1298–1338","1218–1298":"1218–1298","1230–1288":"1230–1288","1338":"1338","17 February 1288":"17. veebruar 1288","after 11 October 1297":"pärast 11. oktoobrit 1297","1288":"1288","1332":"1332","1298":"1298","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1218":"1218","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Stirling Bridge, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Inverness-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1270–after 11 October 1297":"1270–11. lokakuuta 1297 jälkeen","1240–1332":"1240–1332","1270–1297":"1270–1297","1298–1